"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (USA 12)ContentsIntroduction\n              \n3\nThe Bilateral Relationship\n              \n4\n       Our Objectives\n              \n6\nWorking together on Foreign Policy Priorities\n              \n7\n       MEPP\n              \n7\n       Syria\n              \n8\n       Iran\n              \n8\n       Libya\n              \n8\n       Egypt\n              \n9\n       Iraq\n              \n9\n       Afghanistan\n              \n9\n       Pakistan\n              \n10\n       Somalia\n              \n10\n       Sahel\n              \n10\n       Western Balkans\n              \n11\n       Emerging Powers\n              \n11\n       Asia Rebalance\n              \n11\n       Working together in International Institutions\n              \n12\n       Overseas Territories\n              \n14\nThe Defence Relationship\n              \n15\n       Defence Sales to the US\n              \n15\n       ITAR\n              \n16\n       Partnerships with the US\n              \n1\n6\n       NATO\n              \n1\n6\n       Nuclear Cooperation\n              \n1\n6\nWider Security Issues\n              \n1\n8\n       Intelligence Relationship\n              \n18\n       Cyber Security\n              \n18\n       Counter Terrorism\n              \n1\n9\n       Building Stability\n              \n1\n9\n       Extradition\n              \n20\nShared Prosperity\n              \n21\n       Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership\n              \n21\n       Climate and Energy\n              \n21\nWorking Through Our Network to Achieve Our Objectives\n              \n23\n       Staffing across the US Network\n              \n23\n       Soft Power\n              \n24\nConclusion\n              \n26\nIntroduction&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe Bilateral Relationship&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;Our Objectives&#xa0;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWork with the US to safeguard Britain’s national security and support UK objectives worldwide;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nHelp build Britain’s prosperity;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nProvide modern and efficient services to British citizens in the US;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFacilitate\n understanding and communication between the UK and the US; and\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPromote\n Britain’s standing and reputation in the US to build our influence across the country.\n&#xa0;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nStrengthen the bilateral defence relationship;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMaintain close collaboration with US security authorities to reduce the threat to the UK from terrorism, organised crime, and cyber attacks;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nCoordinate closely on the top foreign policy issues, including the Middle East Peace Process, Syria, Iran, Afghanistan, and Iran;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIncrease cooperative engagement with the US in Asia, and support our broader objectives with the emerging powers; and\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nLeverage\n US influence in support of the UK’s objectives in international institutions, including through our Presidency of the G8 and the Foreign Secretary’s Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict Initiative.\n&#xa0;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIncrease UK exports to the US, and inward US investment into the UK;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMake significant \nprogress\n on negotiations towards an ambitious EU/US Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMaintain the UK’s position as the US’s scientific, cultural, and education partner of choice;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEncourage the US to play a leadership role in international climate negotiations;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIncrease collaboration on energy governance, security, and research; and\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPromote\n UK academic institutions in the US, including through the Marshall Scholarship programme.\n&#xa0;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nProvide a high quality consular service;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEnsure the US network is ready to respond effectively to natural disasters or other types of crisis such as terrorist attacks;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nCampaign against use of the death penalty, with particular focus on cases involving British Nationals.\n&#xa0;Working Together on Foreign Policy Priorities&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nMEPP&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;Syria &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nIran&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nLibya&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Egypt&#xa0;Iraq&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nAfghanistan&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nPakistan&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSomalia&#xa0;\nSahel&#xa0; Western Balkans &#xa0;\nEmerging Powers &#xa0;\nAsia Rebalance&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nR\ne-opened our Embassy in Laos; \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nR\necruited over 100 new staff in our missions across the region; \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nR\neinforced our Asia teams in Washington and Brussels; \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nI\nncreased by 50% the number of diplomats in our China network who speak Chinese.\n&#xa0;\n \nThere has also been a significant increase in UK ministerial visits to the region and we have encouraged closer EU-US engagement on \nAsia\n.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWorking Together in International Institutions&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nOverseas Territories&#xa0;The Defence Relationship&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDefence Sales to the US&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;ITAR&#xa0;\nPartnerships with the US&#xa0;\nNATO&#xa0;\nNuclear CooperationWider Security Issues&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nIntelligence Relationship&#xa0;\n“\nSince the 1940s GCHQ and its American equivalents, now the National Security Agency, have had a relationship that is unique in the world.  This relationship has been and remains essential to the security of both nations, has stopped many terrorist and espionage plots against this country, and has saved many lives.  The basic principles by which that cooperation operates have not changed over time. Indeed I wish to emphasise to the House that while we have experienced an extremely busy period in intelligence and diplomacy in the last three years, the arrangements for oversight and the general framework for exchanging information with the United States are the same as under previous Governments.  The growing and diffuse nature of threats from terrorists, criminals or espionage has only increased the importance of the intelligence relationship with the United States.  This was particularly the case in the run up to the Olympics.  The House will not be surprised that our activity to counter terrorism intensified and rose to a peak in the summer of last year\n.”\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nCyber Security&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nCounter Terrorism&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nBuilding Stability&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Extradition&#xa0;Shared Prosperity&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Climate and Energy&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWorking Through Our Network to Achieve Our Objectives&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nStaffing across the US Network&#xa0;\n&#xa0;     FCO Staff (UK-based and Local staff)          Other Government             Department StaffTotalWashington 318\n172\n490Other US Posts 299\n97\n396Total US Network617\n269\n886&#xa0;EU Network1704\n336\n2040India Network659\n241\n900China Network469\n171\n640Notes:\ni)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFCO US Network figures include 60 UK-based FCO staff in Washington and 18 in the Network.\nii)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe M\nO\nD\n has 130 personnel based in the Washington Embassy (included above).  There are a further 573 MOD personnel working in the United States not supported by the FCO Network of posts.  These range from military personnel in operational units or headquarters and exchange officers in each of the Service to technical experts working on joint acquisition projects.\niii)\n&#xa0; \nThe figures provided are a snapshot of the named posts data as recorded on 31 July 2013.  \nThere may be some discrepancies with current figures, in particular between numbers of FCO and other government department locally-engaged staff.  \n  \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSoft Power&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Conclusion&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n3 October 2013\n&#xa0;\n"